  <div class="container-reading">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I find ML engineers and robotics specialists through their code on GitHub, their papers on arXiv, and their models on HuggingFace. Not through CVs or LinkedIn keyword matching.
      </p>

      <p>
        Over the last year I've tested the 2026 AI recruiting stack — Claude, ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity, Juicebox, SeekOut, hireEZ, LinkedIn Hiring Assistant — across 28 client briefs. Response rates on proof-based outreach ran <strong>30–45%</strong>. Standard InMail on the same briefs ran <strong>10–25%</strong>. That's the gap Proof of Work Sourcing closes.
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        Evidence over resumes. Technical recognition over mass outreach.
      </blockquote>

      <h2>Before this</h2>

      <p>
        I built the talent acquisition function from zero at the <strong>Ellison Institute of Technology Oxford</strong> — a medical and life-sciences research institute spun out of Oxford University. Hired across ML research, clinical engineering, and research infrastructure. Wrote the sourcing playbooks, the candidate scorecards, the interview protocols.
      </p>

      <p>
        Before that, I sourced roughly 270 ML engineers and research scientists through <strong>Cubiq</strong>, an agency focused on deep-tech hiring. That's where the GitHub-first methodology started — because ML engineers don't read LinkedIn InMails, but they do notice when you reference the specific repo they've been maintaining for two years.
      </p>

      <h2>What this site is for</h2>

      <p>
        Three things, published weekly:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Automation recipes</strong> built in n8n or Make, copy-paste ready</li>
        <li><strong>Head-to-head tool reviews</strong> — real briefs, real results, honest verdicts</li>
        <li><strong>Contrarian takes</strong> on what AI gets wrong in recruiting</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Plus a growing library of deep-dive playbooks covering the full Proof of Work Sourcing methodology, the 2026 AI tool scorecard, the Boolean-to-AI prompt transition guide, and the n8n recruitment workflow library.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it's free</h2>

      <p>
        Two reasons. First, gated content doesn't build topic authority — it builds friction. The research I've done on how LinkedIn's 2026 algorithm treats credibility was clear about this. Readers who compound expertise over years do it in public, not behind email walls.
      </p>

      <p>
        Second, this isn't a business model. I'm not trying to grow an audience to sell it something later. I write this because I test things in the lab that other recruiters would want to know about, and the cheapest way to share them is a public website.
      </p>

